Same for "Jingle Bell Rock" and "Rockinâ€™ Around the Christmas Tree". They are not bad, but they are also not sufficient. We must strive for more. We will no longer be content with mere humanity. O Tannenbaum. Silent Night.

Life in the traffic tower is not easy, I have to press hundreds of buttons and levers and perform all sorts of quick calculations in my mind to coordinate the traffic on the road while keeping an eye on the street below, but when there is a snowstorm it is very cozy on the job...

This probably betrays my own ignorance on technology, but it's funny that data seems to take less space than energy, e.g. you can fit all the libraries in the world in a txt file on a flash drive, but a flashlight and its battery still doesn't last a century but just a few hours.

You have giant AI-powered chat-bots that can lead a simulated conversation, but Les Stroud is still stuck with the shitty wind-up flashlight at best if he wants to use one for more than a few days. It's not the most intuitive state of affairs, but it seems a general rule of life.
